Abstract = {{Land-use change and intensification threaten bee populations worldwide,
   imperilling pollination services. Global models are needed to better
   characterise, project, and mitigate bees' responses to these human
   impacts. The available data are, however, geographically and
   taxonomically unrepresentative; most data are from North America and
   Western Europe, overrepresenting bumblebees and raising concerns that
   model results may not be generalizable to other regions and taxa. To
   assess whether the geographic and taxonomic biases of data could
   undermine effectiveness of models for conservation policy, we have
   collated from the published literature a global dataset of bee diversity
   at sites facing land-use change and intensification, and assess whether
